@node Starting "Getting Started"

@{fg shine} From the Startup-Sequence@{fg text}

 Put STM into the C drawer, of the floppy disk or hard drive you are going
 to boot with. To run STM simply re-boot your amiga. If you try and boot
 from a floppy drive when you have an hard drive the hard drive will have
 priority over the floppy drive. If you only have floppy drives or only have
 a hard drive then STM will boot as normal.

 @{" CLI Arguments " Link "Arguments"}

@{fg shine} From CLI@{fg text}

 Put STM anywhere you please. In your C drawer, Tools drawer or where ever.
 Start a CLI Process (I.e. use CLI, Shell or Workbench's `Execute' menu)
 and type the pathname for STM (I.e. DF1:Tools/STM, STM, etc) and then press
 ENTER. This will run STM. Alternatively. Type the pathname for STM followed
 by one or more CLI Arguments and then press ENTER.

 @{" CLI Arguments " Link "Arguments"}

@{fg shine} From Workbench@{fg text}

 Make sure there is a TOOL Icon on STM and then double-click on STM. This
 will run STM, which will then read the TOOL Icon for STM ToolTypes. If it
 finds any it will set the appropriate values inside STM.

 @{" ToolTypes    " Link "ToolTypes"}
@endnode

@node Arguments "CLI Arguments"

@{fg fill} Below is a list of STM CLI Keywords with their Arguments. STM will not
 interpret an argument if its keyword is missing. I.e. You cannot just type
 the argument 0100 without typing the keyword SPEECH_PRIORITY for example as
 other keywords might use a 0100 argument. Thus, STM would have an hard time
 differentiating everything.

 You can use more than one keyword/argument set. Example:

 STM SPEECH_PRIORITY 0100 CONSOLE_PAUSETIME 0100

 Keywords and Arguments must be UPPERCASE. As a result of you Typing in
 uppercase STM does not get clogged up with conversion code, opening of the
 Utility.Library, etc.

@{fg shine} CLI Arguments@{fg text}

 SPEECH_PRIORITY Number

 The number can be from 0 upto 255. The default is 100. Using an high number
 (past 100) means most programs will get locked out (will not run) whilst
 your speech is being spoken. Whereas a low number (under 100) means Audio
 breaks might occur in your speech.

 CONSOLE_PAUSETIME Number

 The number can be from 0 upto 900. The default is 100. When the console
 window is used to show you the Mouth Information it needs to know how long
 to pause for. Hence PAUSETIME.
@{fg fill}
 Default values are used when a Keyword/Argument is not used/entered.@{fg fill}
@endnode

@node ToolTypes "WorkBench ToolTypes"

@{fg fill} Below is a list of STM WB ToolTypes with their Arguments. STM will not
 interpret an argument if its tooltype is missing. I.e. You cannot just use
 the argument 0100 without using the tooltype SPEECH_PRIORITY for example as
 other tooltypes might use a 0100 argument. Thus, STM would have an hard
 time differentiating everything.

 Tooltypes and Arguments must be in UPPERCASE. As a result of you Typing in
 uppercase STM does not get clogged up with conversion code, opening of the
 Utility.Library, etc.

@{fg shine} WB ToolTypes@{fg text}

 SPEECH_PRIORITY=Number

 The number can be from 0 upto 255. The default is 100. Using an high number
 (past 100) means most programs will get locked out (will not run) whilst
 your speech is being spoken. Whereas a low number (under 100) means Audio
 breaks might occur in your speech.

 CONSOLE_PAUSETIME=Number

 The number can be from 0 upto 900. The default is 100. When the console
 window is used to show you the Mouth Information it needs to know how long
 to pause for. Hence PAUSETIME.
@{fg fill}
 Default values are used when a ToolType/Argument is not used/entered.@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Funcs "Functions"

@{fg shine}         SEX@{fg text}  Male or Female Voice.@{fg fill}

              This function only tells the Amiga to change certain parts
              of the voice - You must still change the PITCH and RATE of
              the voice to get the correct sounding Sex.@{fg text}
@{fg shine}
        MODE@{fg text}  Natural - Produces a Normal Pitch. This means Words/Sentences
                        are pronounced/said with Syllable Pronunciation,
                        Word Ending fade out, etc (As `We' `Normally' Speak,
                        in other words).

              Robotic - Produces a Monotone Pitch. This means Words/Sent-
                        ences are pronounced/said without changing the Tone
                        of the voice. So you get a Robotic sounding voice.

               Manual - Gives the user more (Manual) control over the voice.
                        This function is used with the Amiga's Accent
                        functions which in turn are used with the Amiga's
                        Mouth functions@{fg fill}

               Manual Mode turns off the above Natural Mode pronunciation
               routines, etc thus giving more voice control to the user.
@{fg shine}
      VOLUME@{fg text}  The Volume of the Voice. Range: 0 to 64.  Default Value: 64.
@{fg shine}
       PITCH@{fg text}  The Baseline Pitch of the Voice. Range: 65 to 320 Hertz.
              Default Value: 110.
@{fg shine}
        RATE@{fg text}  The rate, in Words Per Minute, at which the voice Speaks.
              Range: 40 to 400 Wpm. Default Value: 150.
@{fg shine}
   FREQUENCY@{fg text}  The Frequency of the Voice. Range: 5000 to 28000 Hertz.

              The Default is 22,200 Hertz. If you change this value you can
              create different Vocal effects. However, it is recommended
              that you leave the frequency at 22,200 Hertz and change the
              Echo Frequencies instead to get different Vocal effects.
@{fg shine}
       VOICE@{fg text}  STM allows you to define upto 10 Voices. Use this function to
              edit the voice's name. The new name will also be updated in
              menu. Use the menu options to select a Voice. The voice layout
              is meant for those people working on multi-language programs,
              so that they can easily switch between voices when testing a
              Sentence for example.
@{fg shine}
  ENTHUSIASM@{fg text}  The amount of Enthusiasm a voice has. Default Value is 32.

              This is really meant for use with Manual Mode above. It
              controls the scaling of Pitch Excursions used on Accented
              Syllables. A value of 33 or more gives more Enthusiasm and
              a value of 31 or less gives less Enthusiasm.
@{fg shine}
  ARTICULATE@{fg text}  Controls the Slur factor - It allows you to control the timing
              between each spoken word, etc. Default Value is 100%. A value
              of 101% or more will cause Slur sounding speech and a value of
              99% or less will cause Sharper, Deliberate sounding speech. If
              a value of Zero is given the Narrator.Device will take steps
              to create no timing at all.
@{fg shine}
     PERTURB@{fg text}  Controls the `Shakeyness' of the voice. None-Zero values cause
              a Shakey/Nervous type of voice (like an Old Person speaks for
              example) by randomizing the Pitch.  Range: 0 to 255.
@{fg shine}
      AVBIAS@{fg text}  Amplitude of Voicing - Controls the Amplitude of Un/Voiced
              Speech Sounds. Range: -32 to 31.
@{fg shine}
      AFBIAS@{fg text}  Amplitude of Frication - Controls the Amplitude of Un/Voiced
              Speech Sounds. Range: -32 to 31.

              BIAS Notes: Voiced Sounds are those made with the Vocal Cords
                          vibrating, such as vowels and some consonants like
                          y, r, w and m. Unvoiced Sounds are made without
                          vibrating vocal cords and instead are made with
                          turbulent air, such as s, t, sh and f. Some sounds
                          are a combination of both, such as z and v.
@{fg shine}
     AMPLIFY@{fg text}  Changes the 3 Amplitudies (Width/Size) of the Echo
              Frequencies, in Decibels. Thus, useful for creating different
              Tonal Balances (Bass or Treble). Range: -32 to 31. A value of
              -32 is equivalent to Infinity, shutting that Echo Frequency
              off completely.

              Note: Positive values may cause clipping.
@{fg shine}
       VOWEL@{fg text}  This is the Vowel that VOWEL.CENT, below, uses.

              Note: Use the Blank Vowel if you do not need the VOWEL.CENT
                    function.
@{fg shine}
 VOWEL CENT.@{fg text}  This is the degree of Vowel Centralization. This function
              interpolates towards the VOWEL sound, above. Misleads VOWEL,
              in other words, to make a user specified vowel sound. Thus,
              helping (with the other functions) to create a regional
              accent/dialect. Range: 0 to 100.

              Note: If you do not need this function remember to set the
                    VOWEL function to the Blank Vowel.
@{fg shine}
        ECHO@{fg text}  Changes the Tuning of the Echo Frequencies in the voice. There
              are 3 frequencies that you can change. Number One is the
              Lowest in frequency. Positive values raise the frequencies and
              Negative values lower the frequencies. Range: -32 to 31.
@{fg shine}
 A/C. CHANS?@{fg text}  Select the number of AUDIO CHANNELS you would like to use. You
              can use up to 4 channels.
@{fg shine}
  A/C. VALUE@{fg text}  Enter your Audio Channel Value for the currently selected
              (Grey Button) Audio Channel. Each audio channel is split into
              four sub-channels, as follows:

              Sub-Channel    1 (Right)    2 (Left)    3 (Left)    4 (Right)

              S/C Value           1           2           4            8


              To use an audio channel you simply supply A/C Value with one
              or more of the above S/C Values. So. To use audio channel 1
              with sub-channels 1 and 3 you enter 5 as the A/C Value. This
              is because you add each s/c value. To use audio channel 1 with
              sub-channels 2 and 3 you would enter 6 as the A/C Value. To
              use audio channel 1 with all the sub-channels you would enter
              15 as the A/C Value.

              You do the above for each audio channel you want to use. To
              get stereo sound you use all four audio channels with these
              respective A/C Values - 3, 5, 10 and 12.

              NOTE: You cannot use an audio channel on its own, except for
                    audio channel 1. For example. You cannot use audio
                    channel 3 on its own. The audio channel order is 1, 2,
                    3 and 4. If you are not Audio literate (like me) then
                    stick with using 4 audio channels with a/c values 3, 5,
                    10 and 12 (the Amiga defaults).
@{fg shine}
       SPEAK@{fg text}  Translates the current Language Text into Phonetic Text and
              then calls the SpeakToMe() routine. This acts like a `Repeat
              the Speech' function so that you can hear speech again and
              again without having to go via the Language Text (String)
              Gadget, below.
@{fg shine}
       SPEAK@{fg text}  Calls the SpeakToMe() routine. This acts like a `Repeat the
              Speech' function so that you can hear speech again and again
              without having to go via the Phonetic Text (String) Gadget,
              below.

 Language Text:

 1) Enter your Language Text in this String Gadget.

 2) When you have entered your Language Text either press the Return Key or
    simply Click anywhere outside of the string gadget (on a blank part of
    the Window for example).

    * If you press the Return Key your language text will automatically be
      translated into Phonetic Text and then spoken.

    * If you click anywhere outside of the string gadget your language text
      will not be translated or spoken. To have it translated and spoken
      simply re-click inside the string gadget and press the Return Key as
      above. Or click on the SPEAK button.

 Note: The Language Text string gadget has a length of 70 Characters.


 Phonetic Text:

 1) Enter your Phonetic Text in this String Gadget. Note: Phonetic Text uses
    UPPERCASE letters.

 2) When you have entered your Phonetic Text either press the Return Key or
    simply Click anywhere outside of the string gadget (on a blank part of
    the Window for example).

    * If you press the Return Key your phonetic text will automatically be
      be spoken. Note: The Amiga cannot translate phonetic text into
      language text.

    * If you click anywhere outside of the string gadget your phonetic text
      will not be spoken. To have it spoken simply re-click inside the
      string gadget and press the Return Key as above. Or click on the
      SPEAK button.

 Note: The Phonetic Text string gadget has a length of 140 Characters.

