@node Tips "Speech Tips"

 This section contains my experiences of writing the LGUI Tagalog speech
 files (using the Translator.Library and Narrator.Device) which will
 hopefully give you more speech knowledge by way of hints/tips and
 information so that you might be able to create more precise
 pronunciation/speech for your own projects.
@{fg shine}
 Speech (Accent and Pronunciation)@{fg text}

 The Amiga, by default, is American. Regardless what language you ask the
 Amiga to speak it will always speak that language in an American way, due
 to its american Pronunciation, etc. For example. Even if you were to 
 fine-tune the Amiga to a near perfect Spanish Accent, at the end of the day
 a spanish sentence would be spoken in a spanish accent but the
 pronunciation of some words might not be pronounced properly.

 Saying the above, do not let this put you off. The Amiga is capable of
 pronouncing many words (I would not put an exact figure on it but the
 TAGALOG (Philippines) language for my LGUI program is about 95% accurate
 in speech/pronunciation). All the above is trying to point out is that at
 best you will more than likely have an American-Spanish voice for example
 as opposed to a 100% perfect Spanish voice. And that maybe now and again
 you will come up with a word that the Amiga cannot pronounce 100%
 perfectly. But look at it this way - Can you speak/pronounce every
 syllable/word of your language 100% perfectly?!
@{fg shine}
 Translator.Library (Language Text)@{fg text}

 The Translator.Library has one function, which is to translate Language
 Text (I.e. English, Spanish or whatever) into Phonetic Text. Phonetic Text
 is explained later, so for now just concentrate on Language Text.

 Language Text is normally for words that you can simply type into the Amiga
 and have them spoken without any worry/ies of Pronunciation, Stress, etc.
 Language Text falls into two categories. One is: Spell and Speak the same.
 For example. The word `Hello' is spelt Hello and spoken Hello. And two is:
 Spell and Speak differently. For example. The word `Flower' is spelt Flower
 but spoken something like Floora. So in this case you spell differently
 (I.e. Flouwer) in order to speak differently (I.e. Flou Wer). Normally your
 word/s will fall into category one. It is only when you come across a word
 like Flower or a Foreign word that that word may fall into category two.
 Category two is a case of Trial and Error. For example. With the word
 Flower do you spell Flouwer, Flou Wer or Flouw Er? They might get spoken
 differently from one another. Also. With category two wording a word may
 need to be syllablised, as with Flou Wer, in order to get more precise
 pronunciation. In general, with English, the Amiga will probably be near
 perfect without too much word syllablisation. However. With foreign words
 you are more than likely going to have to syllablise your words, to get
 maximum pronunciation.
@{fg shine}
 Syllablisation@{fg text}

 Here are some methods I have used to get better pronunciation of a word or
 sentence.

 * If you need a word to be Syllablised but at the same time kept whole
   you could try adding an extra E or O to the word's ending, changing an
   E to Ee or an O or U to Oo, etc.

   Example TAGALOG word: Marumi (Mah Ru Me).

     Mah Ru Me - Good, but a bit too slow/syllablised in sound. Also. If you
                 put the word as an whole (MahRuMe) it does not give the
                 correct word sound.

   Mah Roo Mee - Great! By changing `Ru' to `Roo' and `Me' to `Mee' you get
                 the correct syllablised sound. Also. If you put the word as
                 an whole (MahRooMee) you get the correct word sound aswell.
                 If you put MahRooMe you will not get the correct word
                 sound. So as you can see an E or OO, etc in the right place
                 works wonders!

 * If you find the word OR sounds a bit flat, you could try Oar.

 * Tie or Tigh?

        Example TAGALOG word: Hintay (Hin Tie or Hin Tigh).

        Tie and Tigh are the same, except Tigh gives a stress level of 3
        whereas Tie gives a stress level of 4.

 * Ee or Eeee?

        Example TAGALOG word: Kita (Kee Tah).

        If you need a word stretching you could try adding to more Es. For
        example. `Kee Tah' and `Keeee Tah' will give you two different
        sounds.

 * s  - To get rid of a Z sound try adding another S.

        Example word: Los Angeles.

        Los sounds like Loz, whereas Loss will sound like Los. Angeles would
        need to be changed to Anjeless.

 * h  - Might make a word more definate/stressed.

        Example TAGALOG word: Kaibigan (Kah E Big An).

        Adding an H to `An', of Kah E Big An, gives a more definate/stressed
        `Ahn' sound. H is quite flexible and can be used in varied ways to
        give a word definition/stress. An example of this was with `An'
        becoming `Ahn'.

 * A or Ah?

        To give a word like MA an apple (Ah) sound you would change MA into
        MAH. The H changes the sound of the vowel in this case and not the
        stress level as you might of thought (as with, *h, above).

 * e  - Might add extra Stress to a word ending in E.

        Example TAGALOG word: Bili (Be Le).

        Adding another E to an end word with an E already on it does not,
        usually, add any extra stress to that end word. For example. `Be Le'
        and `Be Lee' are the same because no extra stress is added to `Le'.
        However. Adding another E to a non-end word with an E already on it
        might add extra stress to that non-end word. For example. When
        `Be Le' becomes `Bee Le' extra stress is added to `Bee'.

 * ih - Might slightly soften a word ending in E.

        Example TAGALOG word: Nakabili (Nah Ka Billy).

        To get the word in syllable form, but at the same time keeping the
        word sounding whole, you could use:

         Naka Be Le - The trouble with this is that `Be' sounds too
                      definate. I.e. Naka BE Lee.

        Naka Bee Le - The trouble with this is that `Bee' sounds over
                      stressed.

        Naka Bih Le - This is the correct sound. By softening `Be' to `Bih'
                      you get a more natural sound.
@{fg shine}
 Narrator.Device (Phonetic Text)@{fg text}

 Phonetic Text is the code, which is made up of Phonemes, that is used by
 the Narrator.Device. Language Text gives roughly the same speech as
 Phonetic Text, but where they differ is in the control of speech. In
 particular, the Stress levels. With Language Text you are relying on the
 translator library's Translate() function to make your speech for you. So
 naturally the Stress levels are controlled by the Translate() function.
 With Phonetic Text however you have direct control of the Stress levels
 within your speech. To some degree you can alter a word/s in Language Text
 to adjust the Stress level/s, Tigh and Tie for example, but nothing beats
 direct control.

 You do not need the Translator.Library if you are to use Phonetic Text only
 (you will only need the Narrator.Device). However. If you are to use
 Language Text you will need both the Translator.Library and the Narrator-
 .Device. Do not worry too much about this though as the speech program you
 use should give you all the information you need about needed files, etc.
@{fg shine}
 Stress Levels@{fg text}

 Stress levels are used to Stress a word in a certain way. Sometimes to
 hightlight a word or sometimes just to make a pronunciation sound right.
 Here are the stress levels and their recommended use.

 9 - Use for Exclamations.

 7 - Use for Adverbs and Quantifiers.

 5 - Use for Nouns and Adjectives.

 4 - Use for Verbs.

 3 - Use for Pronouns.

 2 - Use for secondary stress in Polysyllabic words, and no stress for
     Articles, Prepositions and Conjunctions.

 1 - Use for secondary stress in Polysyllabic words, and no stress for
     Articles, Prepositions and Conjunctions.

 0 - Use for everything else.

 When using Stress Levels it is usually a case of Experimentation. In some
 cases you may not notice the diference between level 4 and level 5 for
 example. You might, for example, need to try level 6 in these cases to
 notice the difference.

 In addition to stress levels are some special codes.

 . - A full stop at the end of a sentence should cause a slight drop in
     Pitch whilst allowing the end of the sentence to be spoken/heard
     clearly (as opposed to a natural fade-out of the end of the sentence).

 ? - A question mark at the end of a sentence should cause a slight rise
     in Pitch whilst allowing the end of the sentence to be spoken/heard
     clearly (as opposed to a natural fade-out of the end of the sentence).

 , - A comma will cause a pause in a sentence, wherever you have inserted
     a comma.

 --  A pair of dashes should cause a phrase to drop in Pitch very slightly.
     The phrase must be enclosed in dashes. For example:

     this sentence should - drop in pitch very slightly - You know

 ()  Noun Phrase delimiter.

 Note: You may have noticed that I put `Will' and `Should' in the above
       descriptions. Where I have put `Should' means that when I tested the
       codes the difference they made to a sentence was not heard/noticed
       and/or did not have the out-come I would of expected.
@{fg shine}
 Phonemes@{fg text}

 As said above, Phonetic Text is made up of Phonemes. Phonemes are the Vowel
 and Consonant sounds, etc needed to produce Amiga speech. For example. The
 Language Text sound MAH when translated to Phonetc Text is MAE4. MAE4 is
 using the Consonant Phoneme M, the Vowel Phoneme AE and Stress Level 4.

 Below is some information regarding Amiga sound using Phonetic sound.
 I have tested most of the sounds to give you some idea of what each sound
 will/can make. Those sounds I did not, or could not, test I have relied on
 various Amiga books to guide me.

 Please note. As I am not an expert in Amiga Speech I have had to rely on
 various Amiga books and my Ear to give the following information. Thus, it
 is up to you how you interpret the information, etc. The LGUI, TAGALOG,
 FSSpeech.Lgui file might also be of help/guidance to you?


